{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cdbbc547-7336-49b3-b589-689cab8cd979","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events** API in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or anywhere you configure the app builder):\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnStop\n        }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` compiler directives so platform code only compiles for its target.\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnCreate`, etc.).\n- This approach keeps everything in shared code without needing custom platform Activity/AppDelegate subclasses.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c8e9524c-5cd4-4905-93f9-427952ff8d15","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":366,"requestId":"0841:1A5086:A549B9:BF2AFF:69F2A87A"},"id":"71c12be9-76f1-4462-8199-8599829a31ce","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:55:29.922Z","parentId":"609553ca-956d-4018-82a2-813a1eb66414"}
